      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The history of unions in the US is a story of struggle and triumph, with the labor movement fighting for workers' rights and fair treatment since the late 19th century. The Knights of Labor, founded in 1869, was one of the first national labor organizations, but it was the Industrial Workers of America (IWA) and the Congress of Industrial Organizations (CIO) that truly shaped the modern union landscape. The National Labor Relations Act (NLRA) of 1935, signed into law by President Franklin D. Roosevelt, solidified the right to collective bargaining, and unions have since played a crucial role in shaping American politics and economy. Today, unions are stronger than ever, with over 14 million members and a growing presence in the private sector; however, they still face challenges from anti-union policies and the rise of the gig economy.",
